description: From Middle English outbringen, outebringen, from Old English ūtbrengan (“to bring out”), equivalent to out- +‎ bring. Cognate with Dutch uitbrengen (“to release, launch, bring out, utter”), German ausbringen (“to propose, give, space out”), Swedish utbringa (“to propose”).

verbs.description: outbring (third-person singular simple present outbrings, present participle outbringing, simple past and past participle outbrought)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To bring out; deliver; utter; express.
examples: All these, with many more, she deftly wrought Into gay wreaths and posies passing fair; Then from the inner sacristy outbrought Vases of simplest clay, but shapes most rare, And round the statue's base, as quick as thought, [...]
